notesStmt.note: This Carolingian manuscript, probably written in northeastern France in the late ninth century, may have important royal affiliations. A distych, or a two-line verse, found on fol. 60v refers to "REX SAPIENS," and has been seen as evidence that this manuscript is a copy of one made for Charles the Bald. In addition to this remarkable pedigree, the manuscript is also noteworthy for its inclusion of several rare texts, including works by St. Augustine of Hippo, the Coptic theologian Didymus the Blind, and Quodvultdeus, a fifth-century bishop of Carthage. The single illumination in the manuscript, an elaborate title page, is a modern addition.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is Latin.

msItem.title: Liber de opere sancti Augustini
msItem.note: An assortment of works primarily by St. Augustine, with additional works by Didymus the Blind, Quodvultdeus, and several anonymous authors

msItem.title: Title page and table of contents
msItem.note: Added leaf with title and table of contents written in a thirteenth- or fourteenth-century hand; additional note below others added in the fifteenth or sixteenth century: "Item Acta sancti Augustini contra Fortunatum in modu dialogi"

msItem.title: Illuminated title page
msItem.note: Decorative title page added in late nineteenth or early twentieth century at time of rebinding

msItem.title: In Iohannis epistulam ad Parthos 1.12 (excerpt)
msItem.incipit: Qui diligit fratrem suum in lumine manet
msItem.note: Excerpt of text, on lines 1-13, ending with "...in unitate caritatis est fraterna dilectio."

msItem.title: De genesi ad litteram, X, v, 8 (excerpt)
msItem.note: Excerpt of text, on lines 14-16, ending with "...flatus ipse processit."

msItem.title: Contra adversarium legis et prophetarum libri duo, I, xiv, 18 (excerpt)
msItem.incipit: Dictum est cum laude de domino
msItem.note: Excerpt of text, on lines 16-20, ending with "...non nouerat per experientiam."

msItem.title: Sermo CLVI (excerpts)
msItem.note: Two different excerpts from same text; Sermo CLVI, xii, 13: lines 20 (fol. 24v)-1 (fol. 25r), ending with "...sed miserentis dei est"; Sermo CLVI, xiv, 15 through xv, 16: lines 1-5 (fol. 25r), beginning with "Sed accepistis spiritum..." and ending with "...spiritui nostro quia sumus filii dei."

msItem.title: Liber de spiritu sancto interprete Hieronymo (excerpts)
msItem.incipit: Nam eundem evangelii locum Matheus Lucas describens
msItem.note: Many small excerpts beginning on fol. 25r, line 5, and ending on fol. 25v, line 27; excerpts are, as found in Migne, Patrologia Græca 39: 1035 D 3 - 1036 A 8; 1037 A 1-4, B 7-13, C 2-7, 10-12; 1040 A 6-15; 1060 B 7-13; 1060 B 15 - 1061 B 2; 1062 A 15 - B 5; 1063 A 7-8; 1066 A 9-10; 1082 C 10-15; 1083 A 1-D 1

msItem.title: De Genesi contra Manichaeos
msItem.rubric: Primus liber exameron sancti augustini in genesi incipit.
msItem.note: Full text of De Genesi; fols. 26r-39r: Book I; fols. 39r-53v: Book II
Explicit on fol. 53v appears to be scrambled, and small letters above each word seem to indicate correct word order

msItem.title: Anonymous text I
msItem.rubric: Responsiones contra hereticorum inpugnationes quas contra libros augustini de praedestinatis opposverunt incipiunt.

msItem.title: Anonymous text II
msItem.rubric: Faciamus hominem ad imaginem et similitudinem nostram.
msItem.note: Text is divided into thirty-three smaller parts, each with a title

msItem.title: Distych referring to Charles the Bald
msItem.note: The distych is found on lines 23-24, and reads: PERLEGE REX SAPIENS. SOPHIAE PIA DOGMATA SANCTAE/SICQUE FIDEM FIRMA PECTORE ET ORE TUO.
A note in the Walters file by Bernard Bischoff suggests this is a reference to Charles the Bald (see also Jeauneau, 1982, in bibliography)

msItem.title: Adversus quinque haereses
msItem.incipit: Debitor sum fratres fateor non necessitate

msItem.title: De duabus animabus
msItem.rubric: Incipit liber aurelii augustini de duabus animabus.

msItem.title: Contra Fortunatum
msItem.rubric: Incipit Augustini presbyteri catholici [contra Fortunatum (an early addition)]

msItem.title: Psalm 18.2
msItem.note: The same text was added in the tenth or eleventh century, three times by three hands: "celi enarrant gloriam dei"; two versions include musical notation

support.p: Medium- to heavy-weight parchment, hairsides sometimes poorly finished, many flaws and repairs

supportDesc.foliation: First two folios have been foliated but are not original and are not integral to the structure of the first quire, so they are counted as flyleaves here

collation.p: 1(2), 2-4(8), 5(8, -1), 6-10(8), 11(8, -8), 12-14(8), 15(4, -4) Roman numerals added in seventeenth century to bottom middle of versos at end of each quire None First quire composed of an added bifolio, which has been foliated "1" and "1 bis," so first original quire of manuscript begins on fol. 2; quires begin on fols. 1(1), 2(2), 10(3), 18(4), 26(5), 33(6), 41(7), 49(8), 57(9), 65(10), 73(11), 80(12), 88 (13), 96(14), 104(15)

handDesc.handNote: Caroline minuscule, with titles, incipits, and explicits in rustic capitals

decoDesc.decoNote: Foliate initial in gold and silver, created in the style of eleventh-century German illumination
Undecorated; illuminated title page is a nineteenth-century invention; a few titles lightly washed with yellow; text entirely in brown ink of varying shades

decoNote.title: Binding with eighteenth-century Serbian plaque of Christ

note.p: Velvet binding is nineteenth-century, but plaque is earlier, and came from a Serbian flabellum.
Title page added in nineteenth century by artist attempting to recreate a medieval illuminated initial, likely to make the book more desirable for collectors.

binding.p: Late nineteenth- or early twentieth-century red velvet binding by León Gruel, Paris; cover was embellished by Gruel with an eighteenth-century silver and gilt plaque of Christ, originally from a Serbian flabellum, and which contains a Slavonic inscription; front and back pastedowns taken from an early eleventh-century Central Italian Sacramentary; a description of an earlier cover was recorded in the library catalog of the monastery of Saint-André Villeneuve-lès-Avignon in 1640 by Dom Odon de la Mothe, who described it as "postibus copertum et basana alba a parte putrida"

origin.origDate: Second half of the 9th century CE

history.provenance: Created in northeastern France, probably in the region of Reims or Champagne (later French Flanders), ca. 875; a distych on fol. 60v, which speaks of "REX SAPIENS," is believed to refer to Charles the Bald, and it is likely this manuscript is a copy of one made for that Carolingian emperor

Owned by the monastery of Saint-André Villeneuve-lès-Avignon, France, by the seventeenth century; early ownership inscription, fol. 2r, reads "Iste liber est monasterii sancti Andree dyocesis auinionensis .aab."; slightly later inscription (after 1635) reads "Monasterii Sancti Andreae congregationis S. Mauri"; in the bottom margin a slightly later (after 1640) inscription reads "Catalogus inscriptus," a reference to the library's catalog (Bibliotheque nationale de France, lat. 13070, fol. 109r) which contained a description of the manuscript (see binding information from this source below)
Bénigne-Charles Févret de Saint-Mémin of Dijon, eighteenth century; his bookplate (or possibly facsimile of it) on upper board pastedown, probably reinserted (?) by Gruel after rebinding
León Gruel, Paris, late nineteenth or early twentieth century
Henry Walters, Baltimore, purchased from Gruel before 1931
history.acquisition: Walters Art Museum, 1931, by Henry Walters' bequest
